>, see   Marron  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jesus, Armando, Juan, Mario, Carlos, Enrique, Joaquin, Rafael, Alfonso, Alfredo, Alvaro.  Irish Ciaran, Parnell.","Irish (Monaghan): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mearáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mearán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>mear</i> ‘lively’. Compare   Merry  . There may have been some confusion with   Marrin  .","Spanish (<b>Marrón</b>): nickname from <i>marrón</i> ‘brown’, a word of French origin."]},{"name":"Marn","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of <b>Marne</b>, which is perhaps a variant of   Mearns   with loss of final <i>-s</i> or else possibly a variant of   Morrin   1.","Slovenian: nickname from an old spelling of the archaic adjective <i>maren</i> meaning ‘diligent’, but also ‘worthless’. Compare   Maren  ."]}]},{"name":"Roland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowland","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roland de Mearns was born in 1195, in Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland, his father, Nicolas de Mearns, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Nicolas 